  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Luke 22:63-65",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 22:63-65",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And the men that held Jesus mocked him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— What has just been related concerning Peter, passed while the priests examined Jesus, of which examination, before Luke gives an account, he mentions the following remarkable circumstance, namely, that the men who held Jesus ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "mocked him and smote him. And when they had blindfolded him, struck him on the face ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— These circumstances are placed by Matthew and Mark after the council’s condemning him. Perhaps he was abused in the same manner both before and after his condemnation. Certainly “his judges and their retinue were abundantly capable of being thus unjust and barbarous toward him. Nevertheless, what Luke has said here, does not necessarily oblige us to suppose this. He might conclude his account of Peter’s denials with relating what followed upon our Lord’s being condemned, because it happened immediately after the last denial; and to show what a load of indignity was laid at once on the Son of God; namely, that while the most zealous of all his disciples was denying him with oaths and imprecations, the servants and others were insulting him in the most barbarous manner.” — Macknight. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Saying, Prophesy, who is it that smote thee? ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— “This usage of Christ,” says Dr. Hammond, “refers to that sport so ordinary among children, called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "μυινδα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in which it is the manner, first to blindfold, then to strike, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:63",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) then to ask who gave the blow, and not to let the person go till he had named the right man who had struck him. It was used on this occasion to reproach our blessed Lord, and to expose him to ridicule.” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Many other things spake they blasphemously against him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— The expression is remarkable. They charged him with blasphemy, because he said he was the Son of God: but the evangelist fixes that charge on them, because he was really so.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "22:63-71 Those that condemned Jesus for a blasphemer, were the vilest blasphemers. He referred them to his second coming, for the full proof of his being the Christ, to their confusion, since they would not admit the proof of it to their conviction. He owns himself to be the Son of God, though he knew he should suffer for it. Upon this they ground his condemnation. Their eyes being blinded, they rush on. Let us meditate on this amazing transaction, and consider Him who endured such contradiction of sinners against himself.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
