  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 63-65.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "After the second examination, the officials of the Sanhedrin mock and ill treat Jesus as one doomed to death.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 63.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And the men that held Jesus mocked him, and smote him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The position of the Redeemer when the cruelties took place, described in this and the two following verses, was as follows: After the arrest in Gethsemane, the guards, Jewish and Roman, escorted the Prisoner to the palace of the high priest in Jerusalem. There both Annas and Caiaphas apparently lodged. In the first instance, Jesus was brought before Annas, who was evidently the leading personage of the Sanhedrin of that day. Details of the preliminary examination are given apparently by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 18:13, 19-24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In this first and informal trial Caiaphas was evidently present, and took part (ver. 19). At the close of this unofficial but important proceeding, Annas sent him to Caiaphas. The true reading in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 18:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀπέστειλεν οϋν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"Annas therefore sent him.\" That is, at the close of the first ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "unofficial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " examination, which took place in Annas's apartments in the palace of the high priest, Annas sent him to be examined ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "officially",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " before Caiaphas, the reigning high priest, and a committee of the Sanhedrim This, the second trial of Jesus, is related at some length by St. Matthew (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:59-66",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and St. Mark (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 14:55 64",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The priests on that occasion sought false witnesses, but their witness did not, we know, agree. Jesus kept silence until Caiaphas arose, and with  awful solemnity adjured him to say whether he was the Christ, the Son of God. So adjured, Jesus answered definitely in the affirmative. Then Caiaphas rent his robe, and appealed to the assembly, who answered the appeal by a unanimous cry,\" He is guilty of death.\" After this hearing before Caiapnas and a committee of the Sanhedrin, the condemned One was conducted before the full assembly of the Sanhedrim While being led across the court, he heard Peter's third denial. It was during the interval which elapsed before the great council assembled, that the mocking related in these verses (63-65) took place. Luke 22:63",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
